VI used to be a marathon runner.
p20
aVLong distance running was not only good for my well-being
p21
aVbut it helped me meditate and dream big.
p22
aVSo the longer distances I ran,
p23
aVthe bigger my dreams became.
p24
aVUntil one fateful morning,
p25
aVand while training, I was hit by a bus.
p26
aVI nearly died, was in a coma,
p27
aVstayed at the hospital for two years,
p28
aVand underwent 36 surgeries to be able to walk again.
p29
aa(lp30
VAs soon as I came out of my coma,
p31
aVI realized that I was no longer the same runner I used to be,
p32
aVso I decided, if I couldn't run myself,
p33
aVI wanted to make sure that others could.
p34
aVSo out of my hospital bed,
p35
aVI asked my husband to start taking notes,
p36
aVand a few months later, the marathon was born.
p37
aa(lp38
VOrganizing a marathon as a reaction to an accident
p39
aVmay sound strange,
p40
aVbut at that time, even during my most vulnerable condition,
p41
aVI needed to dream big.
p42
aVI needed something to take me out of my pain,
p43
aVan objective to look forward to.
p44
aVI didn't want to pity myself, nor to be pitied,
p45
aVand I thought by organizing such a marathon,
p46
aVI'll be able to pay back to my community,
p47
aVbuild bridges with the outside world,
p48
aVand invite runners to come to Lebanon
p49
aVand run under the umbrella of peace.
