aa(lp51
VOrganizing a marathon in Lebanon
p52
aVis definitely not like organizing one in New York.
p53
aVHow do you introduce the concept of running
p54
aVto a nation that is constantly at the brink of war?
p55
aVHow do you ask those who were once fighting
p56
aVand killing each other
p57
aVto come together and run next to each other?
p58
aVMore than that, how do you convince people to run a distance of 26.2 miles
p59
aVat a time they were not even familiar with the word "marathon"?
p60
aVSo we had to start from scratch.
p61
aa(lp62
VFor almost two years, we went all over the country
p63
aVand even visited remote villages.
p64
aVI personally met with people from all walks of life \u2014
p65
aVmayors, NGOs, schoolchildren,
p66
aVpoliticians, militiamen,
p67
aVpeople from mosques, churches,
p68
aVthe president of the country, even housewives.
p69
aVI learned one thing:
p70
aVWhen you walk the talk, people believe you.
p71
aVMany were touched by my personal story,
p72
aVand they shared their stories in return.
p73
aVIt was honesty and transparency that brought us together.
p74
aVWe spoke one common language to each other,
p75
aVand that was from one human to another.
p76
aVOnce that trust was built,
p77
aVeverybody wanted to be part of the marathon
p78
aVto show the world the true colors of Lebanon and the Lebanese
p79
aVand their desire to live in peace and harmony.
